<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 92 / Brazil and IMF put off stand-by accord talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BILL HINCHBERGER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAO PAULO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SCHEDULED negotiations between Brazil and the International Monetary Fund
over targets for the country's stand-by accord have been put on hold until
the government can implement cost-cutting measures. Brazil has been unable
to meet targets for cutting the public deficit laid out in the agreement,
signed in January.
A good bill of health from the IMF is fundamental for implementation of
Brazil's accord with international creditor banks, since IMF funds are
needed to supply part of the collateral for the debt repayment scheme.
The government has offered a fiscal reform package, including a tax reform
and simplification proposal and a series of constitutional amendments that
President Fernando Collor de Mello says are needed before the administration
can seriously reduce public spending.
These efforts are hindered by the country's political crisis, as a
congressional inquiry into corruption charges against the president's
campaign treasurer may lead to efforts to impeach Mr Collor.
Meanwhile, Mr Collor has asked the 'silent majority' to demonstrate its
support for him by wearing the colours of the country's flag tomorrow .
But a recent opinion poll in Sao Paulo, by Data Folha, showed that 65 per
cent rated the president's performance in office bad or terrible, opposed to
12 per cent who characterised it as excellent or good.
However, the apparently desperate gesture comes as a growing number of
observers are predicting that Mr Collor can weather efforts to impeach him.
</TEXT>
