<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 92 / Boris Yeltsin's troublesome deputy waits serenely for call
to power: Alexander Rutskoi explains his broadsides against radical reforms
to Leyla Boulton
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RUSSIA'S Vice-President Alexander Rutskoi displays the serene
self-confidence of a man whose time has finally come.
Delivering the benefits of eight months of sniping at the government's
radical economic reforms, a recent opinion poll suggested for the first time
last month that he had become more popular than President Boris Yeltsin.
As the fate of Mr Yegor Gaidar, the acting prime minister, hangs in the
balance, he and the 'constructive' Civic Union opposition group he backs are
certain their calls for a new cabinet and more gradual reform will soon
prevail.
But this Afghan war hero with a taste for sculpture says that at 44, he is
in no hurry to replace Mr Yeltsin, who has already declared he will stand
down at the end of his current presidential term. 'If I serve two terms with
President Yeltsin, I will be 53 years old. What's that for a politician?' he
told the FT this week.
His airy Kremlin office features a bust of Peter the Great, the great
reforming Tsar, a row of model Soviet airplanes and a Sotheby's catalogue -
reflecting the eclectic tastes of the air force general who is in charge of
reforming Russian agriculture.
His motto of 'liberal reform and strong rule' inspired by Pyotr Stolypin,
the great Tsarist prime minister who combined strong-arm rule with ambitious
land reform, Mr Rutskoi claims Mr Gaidar's 'shock therapy' is leading Russia
to revolution and disaster.
He believes Russia must abandon financial austerity policies agreed with the
International Monetary Fund and rely more on its own resources if it cannot
get unconditional help from the west. 'Dancing for the IMF has buried our
investment-credit policy,' he charges.
By way of argument, he rattles off a host of figures on the fall in
production. Asked why he favours the appointment of a new cabinet (an aide
claims this is just a matter of weeks away), he picks up a weekly report on
inflation by Mr Andrei Nechayev, the economics minister. 'I am going to
invite Nechayev here and give him 335 roubles to see if he can buy a week's
shopping as this report claims it is possible to do.'
The flaws in his arguments appear only when he is challenged on how he would
deliver alternatives. He advocates either methods from the past which have
already proven to be inadequate (planning the distribution of natural
resources) or remedies which the new government is already trying (such as
attracting foreign investment).
'He is so simplistic, a typical military man,' said one foreign diplomat
with experience of military regimes.
His extravagant criticisms - typical of many ambitious Russian politicians
who are free from real responsibility - have in themselves done much to
undermine the present government. His aides argue, however, that he has done
President Yeltsin a favour by chanelling public discontent away from the
extreme neo-communists and fascists who find so much in common in
post-communist Russia.
From his military past, when he flew missions in Afghanistan and was
eventually taken prisoner by mujahideen guerrillas, the dapper
vice-president believes in working out a clear cut strategy and marching
towards it.
For this reason, he argues that Mr Yeltsin must have more power to pursue
reforms - a path which the president has already tried without going as far
as abolishing the backward parliament which has stood in his way.
Although no easy task in a country where the vice-president can tell the
nation that the government is committing 'economic genocide', Mr Rutskoi is
probably also right about the need for more 'ideological work' to explain
market reforms to the people.
'Everybody must know what they are going to get out of reforms,' says this
former communist who is now honorary chairman of his social-democratic Free
Russia Party - now one of the biggest of Russia's fledgling parties.
He speaks effortlessly in the theatrical cadences and soothing tones of a
populist leader as if he had been groomed for this role all his life ('the
Russians are a patient people, a courageous people and a good people but
their patience is not unlimited').
'This is a new kind of 'popular politics' - talking to the people in
language they understand,' explains one of his aides who says the next task
is building the vice-president's image in the west.
Although he enthuses about the need to co-operate with the west, Mr Rutskoi
also successfully seizes on a popular perception that the west has let
Russia down with help for its reforms. 'Today everybody claps Russia on the
back and says 'come on come on'. All right, but help us then. I'm sincerely
grateful to those who give humanitarian aid but it is peanuts. We need help,
but for concrete projects so that western taxpayers can see where the help
is going. Like if you build a baby-food factory, you can solve the baby-food
problem.'
In contrast, he becomes visibly angry when he talks about the former Soviet
republics. He says that Russia must act from a position of force in order to
ensure they respect the 'human rights' of Russian minorities. He claims that
it is precisely his sabre-rattling which has helped warring parties come to
the negotiating table in Moldova and South Ossetia.
'No idea is worth a child's tears,' he says, quoting Dostoevsky to condemn
what he calls 'nationalist-chauvinistic' policies pursued by newly
independent republics - such as laws in Estonia depriving Russians of the
vote or requiring that they learn the local language to hold government
office.
Similarly he argues that Russia should cut off deliveries of cheap energy to
the Baltic republics if they continue to insist on the immediate withdrawal
of Russian army units. 'They say housing for them is our problem but if it
is our problem let's export those energy supplies for hard currency and
build flats with the proceeds.'
Just like the young academic, Mr Gaidar, whose team he branded as 'little
boys in pink shorts', he has matured a lot since coming to power, making a
host of mistakes on the way.
In February for instance, a brief flirtation with the far right won him the
opprobrium of his own party. Until December he was close to General
Alexander Sterligov, a hardline neo-communist KGB officer.
Now he is open to exploitation by other forces in the Civic Union alliance,
including Mr Arkady Volsky, the wily chief of the Russian Union of
Industrialists and Entrepreneurs who also has ambitions for high office.
Although President Yeltsin is by no means on the ropes, Mr Rutskoi offers a
package which the fickle and long-suffering Russian public seems
increasingly willing to embrace.
Extracts of this interview will be shown tonight on Channel 4's The World
This Week.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
