<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 92 / French state insurers under fire on HIV cover
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Michel Sapin, the French finance minister, yesterday criticised Union des
Assurances de Paris (UAP), the state-controlled insurance group, for
threatening to withdraw its cover from blood transfusion centres which have
been implicated in a scandal over Aids-tainted blood supplies.
On Thursday morning UAP, which is France's biggest insurer, announced it was
not obliged to pay damages to people who contracted the HIV virus through
transfusions from 25 regional centres where officials allegedly failed to
notify UAP they were knowingly using infected blood.
UAP said late on Thursday that it had reversed its decision. The French
insurers' association yesterday announced that its members were extending
the transfusion centres' cover until the end of the year.
France's regional blood transfusion centres are being sued by people who
were infected with HIV after receiving transfusions, even though the health
officials involved allegedly knew the blood was infected. More than 1,200
people, mostly haemophiliacs, are known to have been infected with HIV by
transfusions - 256 have died.
Damages have been awarded to some HIV victims. Other cases are still
pending, including the case against Dr Michel Garretta, former director of
the National Blood Transfusion Centre, in which Mr Laurent Fabius, former
French prime minister, now first secretary of the ruling Socialist party,
gave evidence.
Had UAP gone ahead with its original threat, the transfusion centres would
have been forced to pay their own damages. Some centres would almost
certainly have gone bankrupt. This would have caused even more embarrassment
for the government, already under fire for the involvement of senior
socialists such as Mr Fabius in the Garretta case.
Mr Sapin yesterday condemned UAP's initial announcement saying it had been
made 'without sufficient consideration'. His public comments underlined the
strength of the government's feeling on the issue. It usually prefers to
resolve disagreements with state companies in private.
</TEXT>
