<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 92 / International Company News: Daily News unions fail to agree
on a new owner
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FUTURE of the Daily News, the New York city tabloid, seemed more
precarious than ever yesterday afternoon when its unions failed to agree on
a new owner after three days of negotiations.
The cash-strapped paper, rescued by Mr Robert Maxwell last year, has been
under Chapter 11 of the US bank ruptcy code since the month after Mr
Maxwell's death.
A creditors meeting has now been rescheduled for Monday, the day bankruptcy
court judge Tina Brozman set for the paper to produce its reorganisation
plan. Earlier this week, the creditors committee had said it would announce
its own choice among the three potential owners on Friday if the unions
failed to reach an agreement.
The paper has received bids from Mr Conrad Black, the Canadian publisher who
owns the Daily News in London, and Mr Mortimer Zuckerman, owner of US News
and World Report magazine and The Atlantic Monthly. There is also a
so-called 'stand alone' plan under which Silver Screen, a group of film
financiers, would join forces with the unions, giving them a stake in the
paper.
The creditors are reviewing revised offers from both Mr Black and Mr
Zuckerman on debt payments and a new printing plant.
In spite of yesterday's apparent impasse, Mr Fred Drasner, president of US
World and News Report, said: 'We are reasonably encouraged by the outcome
because we think we have the support of the majority of the unions.'
</TEXT>
