<HEADLINE>
FT  14 AUG 92 / UK Company News: Blagden at Pounds 6m thanks to all-round
advance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER PEARSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BLAGDEN Industries, the Hertfordshire-based packaging, chemicals and
protective equipment group, bucked recessionary pressures in the six months
to June 28 and lifted pre-tax profits by 11 per cent to Pounds 6m. Turnover
rose from Pounds 109.7m to Pounds 118.1m.
Mr Cameron Smith, chief executive, said he was particularly pleased that
profits improvements had been across the board and not simply led by one
division.
In packaging, the core business, international operating profits rose to
Pounds 4.58m (Pounds 4.47m) on turnover up at Pounds 62m (Pounds 59.4m),
while the UK side made Pounds 1.42m (Pounds 1.29m) on turnover of Pounds
20.8m (Pounds 20.5m). Volumes in the division increased 6 per cent in the
half as prices were reduced.
Mr Smith said that, having made 85 per cent of profits a few years ago, the
45 gallon steel drum business now only accounted for 65 per cent. He said he
was excited about the future of the new propellant for aerosols - compressed
air, rather than flammable gases like butane, opted for after the CFC scare.
In chemicals, 'distribution was hammered by recession', but manufacturing
accounted for the rise in profits from Pounds 1.6m to Pounds 2.14m on
turnover of Pounds 25m (Pounds 23.3m).
Protective equipment sales grew to Pounds 10.2m (Pounds 6.56m). Mr Smith
said: 'Old companies made Pounds 500,000, new ones Pounds 300,000, minus
Pounds 300,000 written off' in one-off obsolescence costs, where Blagden
redesigned many of its ranges.
Because of the international weighting of its profits, Blagden had to write
off Pounds 600,000 of advance corporation tax, against last time's Pounds
250,000, of which Mr Smith said: 'With perfect hindsight, it should have
been Pounds 500,000.' This lifted the tax charge to 42.5 per cent (38 per
cent).
Earnings were static at 7.3p per share and, because of the tax penalty, the
interim dividend is held at 4.5p.
</TEXT>
