<HEADLINE>
FT  14 AUG 92 / Mobile phone groups to cut prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
VODAFONE, the cellular phone network operator, yesterday announced new
prices in an effort to bring mobile telephones to the masses.
The move followed a similar initiative by Cellnet, its main rival, aimed at
opening up a new market of non-business users.
The two groups, which dominate the UK market, are hoping to transform the
cellular phone from an expensive businessman's gadget to a more everyday
consumer item.
The new prices aim to attract customers who would like to own a mobile phone
for occasional use, but find the connection and line rental charges too
high.
Vodafone expects the market for mobile phones to grow from the current 1.3m
users to 7m - half of them non-business users - by the turn of the century.
Starting in October, Vodafone will offer a 'low cost' service with a reduced
connection charge of Pounds 30, compared with the current Pounds 50, and a
monthly line rental charge of Pounds 15, down from Pounds 25. Cellnet is
introducing a similar option from November.
Vodafone's call charges under this service, however, will be higher than
under its present tariff. The peak rate will be 54p per minute within the
M25 London orbital and 46p per minute elsewhere. The off-peak rate is 15p
per minute in all areas.
These rates compare with Vodafone's current rates of 33p per minute within
the M25 at peak times - between 7.30am and 9.30pm, Monday to Saturday - and
25p elsewhere. Off-peak rates are 10p anywhere.
Cellnet's nationwide peak rate charge under its new offer will be 50p per
minute and 20p off peak. Under its existing tariff, peak calls cost 33p per
minute within the M25 and 25p per minute elsewhere. Off-peak calls are 10p.
Vodafone is pricing handsets at Pounds 249 compared with current retail
prices of anywhere from Pounds 800 to Pounds 200. Cellnet's will also be
priced under Pounds 300.
The new pricing scheme is intended to attract people who do not plan to make
frequent calls on their mobile phones.
The higher call charges mean that anyone making at least one call a day
during peak hours is better off staying with the current scheme, Vodafone
says.
Both companies expect the new prices to attract a large number of new
customers. Cellnet estimates it will have 200,000 new customers in the first
year.
The mobile phone market has been hit by recession, and competition is
expected to increase with the launch next year of radio-based personal
communications networks and the progressive introduction of telephones using
GSM, a digital standard agreed by 17 European coun-tries.
Mobiles for the masses, Page 11
</TEXT>
