<HEADLINE>
FT  14 AUG 92 / Wage inflation at lowest rate for 25 years
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WAGE INFLATION, as measured by the underlying increase in seasonally
adjusted average weekly earnings, decelerated sharply to 6 per cent in the
year to June, the lowest such rate for 25 years.
Because manufacturing productivity advanced strongly in the three months to
June, the growth of wages and salaries per unit of output also declined,
bringing the rate of increase in British manufacturing unit wage costs to
their lowest level since October 1987.
Figures released yesterday by the Department of Employment showed that the
underlying annual increase in UK average earnings has fallen by 1.5
percentage points from 7.5 per cent in March, a rate of decline last seen in
1981.
Officials expect the rate of wage inflation will continue to fall following
a recent spate of settlements in the 4 per cent to 4.5 per cent range.
The June average earnings increase was lower than most forecasts and
accompanied a downward revision in the rate of increase in May to 6.25 per
cent from 6.5 per cent announced last month. The Public Finance Foundation,
an independent research body, reported yesterday that average earnings
growth would be even lower than 6 per cent if public-sector wage inflation
were not running at a high 7.3 per cent rate.
Mrs Gillian Shephard, the employment secretary, said yesterday's unit wage
cost figures showed that the competitiveness of the UK economy continued to
improve. In the three months to the end of June manufacturing unit wage
costs were 1.7 per cent up on the same period last year, compared with 4.5
per cent in the three months to March.
Productivity, although higher in June, grew less strongly than in May.
Manufacturing output per head in June was 3.4 per cent higher than in June
last year compared with year-on-year growth of 4.2 per cent in May.
Manufacturing productivity in the second quarter was 4.2 per cent higher
than in 1991, however, compared with a year-on-year increase of 3.9 per cent
in the first quarter.
According to Employment Department officials overtime earnings account for
between 0.5 and 0.75 percentage points of average earnings growth. The
latest statistics, however, showed a sharp drop in overtime working in
manufacturing to 9.95m hours a week in June from 11.26m in May. The hours
lost by short-time working increased to 640,000 a week from 350,000,
resulting in a fall in the index of average weekly hours worked in UK
manufacturing to 99.6 in June from 101 in May.
Only 25,000 working days were lost through industrial disputes in June,
bringing to 546,000 the number of working days lost through industrial
action in the 12 months to mid 1992. This was the lowest total since 1920.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-7864</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CHRANAEVFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920814
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  14 AUG 92 / City's foreign earnings rose to Pounds 16.9bn last year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL, World Trade Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S financial in-stitutions boosted overseas earnings by 12.8 per cent
to Pounds 16.9bn last year, underlining the importance of 'invisibles' to
the economy and of the City's international role as a financial centre.
The improvement largely reflected increased investment income, which rose
almost 20 per cent to Pounds 10.5bn, according to a report from British
Invisibles, an industry trade group. Services income rose just 3 per cent to
Pounds 6.4bn.
Even the insurance sector - dogged by underwriting losses at Lloyd's of
London - saw a 24 per cent jump in earnings to Pounds 3.3bn as insurance
brokers raised income by 12 per cent to a record Pounds 919m.
The banking sector also made a schizophrenic showing, with a 7.9 per cent
fall to Pounds 3.14bn in income from banking services outweighed by a 21 per
cent rise to Pounds 4.6bn in investment income, to show an overall 7.5 per
cent improvement between 1990 and last year.
British Invisibles noted 'positive pointers' for the first half of this
year, with informal forecasts that earnings would grow by at least 7 per
cent.
The UK is second only to the US as an exporter of invisibles - which
encompass not only financial services, but tourism, information transfer and
transport services, and remitted interest, profits and dividends. Last year
these earned Pounds 117bn - significantly more than visible exports of
Pounds 104.8bn - with interest, profits and dividends accounting for Pounds
75bn.
This accounted for about 16 per cent of the Pounds 750bn total world trade
in invisibles.
The UK has a greater dependency on invisibles trade than any industrial
country, with tradeable services accounting for 20.5 per cent of gross
national product last year. This compares with 4.8 per cent of GNP in the
US, and 5.6 per cent in Japan.
Even last year, a year of recession in banking, 31 new banks opened a London
office and 15 banks departed.
The Baltic Exchange, which was devastated by an IRA bomb in April, lifted
earnings by 7 per cent to Pounds 804m. Mr Peter Tudball, the exchange's
chairman, said this confirmed the exchange's importance at the heart of the
world shipping freight market.
Dealers in London's securities markets lifted earnings by 23 per cent to
Pounds 2.0bn, with a steep fall in commissions and fees being offset by
portfolio investment income.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-7865</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CHRANAEUFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920814
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  14 AUG 92 / Sharpest jobless rise in south
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNEMPLOYMENT continued to grow more rapidly in the south of England than
elsewhere in the UK between June and July, according to the Department of
Employment.
Of the 29,100 seasonally adjusted increase in the number of claimants over
18 recorded in the month to July 9, 16,100 occurred in regions south of a
line from the Wash to the Bristol Channel.
Unemployment in the south-east, including greater London, is running at
record levels. Just over 30 per cent of UK unemployment is now con-centrated
in the south-east, where the seasonally adjusted jobless figure was 845,300
last month. Unemployment in greater London was 427,600, or 10.6 per cent of
the area's workforce. In the UK as a whole last month's seasonally adjusted
jobless total was 2.75m, or 9.7 per cent.
Recorded unemployment is much higher among men. The latest figures put the
seasonally adjusted male jobless total at 2.11m in July, or 13 per cent,
against female unemployment of 644,600, or 5.3 per cent.
Yesterday's figures nonetheless suggested that the rise in unemployment may
be past the worst. Last month's increase was sharply lower than the
seasonally adjusted jump of 69,600 in July last year. The average monthly
increase of 19,400 in the last three months was well down on the 29,400
monthly increase in the three months to April. In addition, the number of
employees in manufacturing industry in June fell by only 2,000 to 4.52m, the
smallest such decline since July 1990.
 --------------------------------------------
         UK UNEMPLOYMENT: July 1992
 --------------------------------------------
Northern Ireland                14.7%
North                           11.2%
west Midlands                   10.6%
north-west                      10.5%
Yorks &amp; Humber                   9.8%
Wales                            9.6%
Scotland                         9.5%
south-east                       9.3%
south-west                       9.1%
