<HEADLINE>
FT  14 AUG 92 / Secretarial rises 'above average'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SECRETARIAL PAY, which has risen an average of 6.5 per cent over the past
year, is outstripping inflation and average earnings, according to Reward
Group, David Goodhart writes.
Chief executives' secretaries pay rose 7.3 per cent, while shorthand/audio
typists' increases averaged 5.6 per cent. Average earnings as a whole are
rising at 6 per cent, with clerical staff receiving 4.5 per cent, according
to Reward.
The study shows that the average pay of chief executives' secretaries in
central London has risen from Pounds 11,229 in July 1987, 25 per cent above
the national average, to Pounds 18,624 in July 1992, 40 per cent above the
national average.
In central London, where the cost of living has moved closer to the national
average, the average pay for a manager's secretary is Pounds 14,914.
