<HEADLINE>
FT  14 AUG 92 / Bingham cautious on BCCI probe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LORD Justice Bingham, who is to succeed Lord Donaldson as Master of the
Rolls, said yesterday he did not know when his completed report into the
collapsed Bank of Credit and Commerce International would be published and
whether it would be published in full.
'The question of publication is entirely for others and I have no input
now,' he said. 'But certainly there is material in the appendices which I
would expect to be unpublish-able.'
Lord Justice Bingham, speaking the day after the announcement of his
appointment as the most senior civil court judge in England and Wales,
described the 11-month BCCI inquiry as 'extremely laborious, but very
interesting'. He said it would have been impossible to conduct the inquiry
in public because a great deal of the material could not have been disclosed
without prejudicing possible criminal proceedings.
Lord Justice Bingham, who is in favour of a number of radical reforms, said
that provided there were adequate safeguards to ensure the quality of
advocacy, he was in favour of wider rights of audience for solicitors in the
higher courts.
He would like to see judges and barristers abandon their wigs in the civil
courts but not the criminal courts, and the European Convention on Human
Rights incorporated into domestic law.
