<HEADLINE>
FT  14 AUG 92 / Challenge to LT over pension move
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON and NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RAIL UNIONS are challenging the legality of the deed and rules of London
Transport's pension fund and the procedures by which the salaried grade fund
and wages grade fund were amalgamated to form the present merged fund in
April 1989.
The unions say the rules of the new fund give LT powers it was not entitled
to take, in particular over the pension fund surplus. The merger of the
funds, into a fund of a total of nearly Pounds 1.7bn, was allowed under a
law which the unions believe specified that the new fund should reflect, as
nearly as possible, the balance of power and responsibilities that existed
under the predecessor funds.
The legal dispute arises from LT's decision to award itself the use of 70
per cent of the fund's surplus of about Pounds 460m and use the remaining 30
per cent for improvements to benefits.
The case centres on legislation which is unique to LT, but solicitors acting
for scheme members said the outcome could have implications for other
companies seeking to merge pension schemes.
There has been an increasing trend since the mid 1980s for companies to
switch pension-scheme members into new schemes with less restrictive rules,
allowing the companies to take advantage of surpluses built up as high
investment returns outstripped increases in benefits.
A solicitor for some of the LT members said that in most of those cases
members had been offered some enhancement of benefits. 'In this case, they
did not think the inducement was enough,' he added.
Most scheme members, unhappy with the terms of their transfer, have been
unable to seek redress in the courts because they do not have the funds to
pursue a legal claim. The LT case is among the first to be tested in the
courts.
The case centres on whether the loose body of trust law, which requires
trustees to act in the best interest of beneficiaries, allows the transfer
of those beneficiaries to a scheme which has less generous terms than those
currently on offer.
LT said: 'We maintain our view is reasonable but we would always listen to
new proposals. We hope the dispute is resolved before the court hearing in
December.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
