<HEADLINE>
FT  14 AUG 92 / Plan to tighten law on political levy may be revived
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is prepared to revive plans to tighten the law governing
trade unions' political funds.
Senior Conservatives are warning that a move by Mr John Smith, the Labour
party leader, to convert the unions' political levy payers into 'associate'
Labour party members would prompt legislation to make it easier for
individuals to refuse to make such contributions.
The legislation would require unions to receive the written authority of
each member before using any portion of their contributions for political
purposes. Senior Labour figures accept that such a change could lead to a
sharp reduction in the level of contributions.
Under existing law individuals can contract out of payments to union
political funds, which typically amount to just less than 10 per cent of
annual dues. The system leaves thousands of 'passive' contributors to Labour
finances who might choose not to pay if the law demanded their positive
approval.
Successive Tory governments have considered changing the law. The latest
review was earlier this summer when Mr Michael Forsyth, the employment
minister, pressed for its inclusion in the employment bill due later this
year.
The bill includes measures to tighten the rules on the direct deduction of
union dues by employers but after what was described as a 'finely balanced'
argument the government decided to defer again any move on the political
levy.
Now senior Conservatives are stressing that it would be 'unthinkable' to
allow the present system of passive contributions to continue if Mr Smith
used the levy system to boost the individual membership of the Labour party.
One said: 'It would be impossible to justify the inertia in the system which
already means that many Conservative trade unionists contribute to Labour.'
The Tories add that a Labour suggestion that union levy payers would have to
opt explicitly for associate party membership or would pay an additional fee
would not discourage the government from changing the law.
Labour is considering relaxing its rule that requires those in employment to
join a relevant trade union before becoming a party member. The rule is
thought to discourage a significant number of potential recruits to the
party.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 5
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-7881</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CHRANAEEFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920814
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  14 AUG 92 / Building societies feel the squeeze: David Barchard on
conflicting pressures that have brought unusually narrow margins
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD and ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
YESTERDAY seemed, on the face of it, an odd time to be making a cut in
savings rates. The savings market is shrinking and building societies have
been complaining for months that they have been losing business to National
Savings.
But as Mr Mike Whitehouse, operations director of Halifax, the largest
society, announced an average 0.35 percentage point cut in the savings rates
he said: 'The alternative was just not realistic.'
Building societies saw a Pounds 314m net outflow of funds in June and they
fared even worse in July. The figures will not be published for another
fortnight but are expected to show a net outflow of about Pounds 450m,
leaving a net outflow of about Pounds 105m for the first seven months of
this year.
National Savings has easily outstripped building society receipts in every
month except January. The pressure on societies is compounded by the fact
that many people are repaying debt rather than saving.
Mr David Barnes, finance director of Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester, the sixth
largest society, said: 'We are all chasing just a little money around.'
In this situation societies would normally improve their rates to investors
to attract more business and pass on the cost to mortgage customers. On
Tuesday Skipton, the 14th largest society, tried to do this but the larger
societies would not follow.
Since February building societies and Abbey National, the retail bank which
was formerly a society, have been holding standard mortgage rates about 50
basis points above the London Inter-bank Offered Rate. A few years ago many
societies would have considered that their rates to borrowers should be at
least one full percentage point, and perhaps even two, above Libor.
The present unusually narrow margin was introduced by Abbey National in
February as a sort of discount to borrowers in the hope of reviving the
housing market. Such a tight rate not only squeezes profits but reduces the
amount of income societies can put aside against their unprecedentedly high
levels of bad debts.
Six months later there is no sign of a market revival but the large
societies feel strongly that rates to borrowers should not go up.
One reason is that they have recently prevailed on the government to lower
National Savings rates - not once but twice. The unspoken quid pro quo was
that mortgage rates would stay down, and Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester, which had
announced a mortgage rate rise, withdrew it smartly.
Halifax said: 'Increasing rates to borrowers is just not realistic, partly
because we want to encourage a housing market recovery and secondly because
we want to make continued progress in dealing with arrears and serious
arrears.'
Any rise in lending rates would have been modest but societies say it would
have made it even more difficult to manage the accounts of about 305,000
mortgage customers with arrears of more than six months.
Mr Donald Kirkham, group chief executive of Woolwich, the third largest
society, said: 'Raising mortgage rates by say 0.5 per cent may not look very
onerous but even an additional payment of perhaps Pounds 8 a month could be
the last straw for some people.'
The savings outflow is a problem which the larger societies can live with.
Their liquidity is mostly good and their mortgage business is about 60 per
cent of what it was two years ago. They can turn to the wholesale money
markets to fund these reduced volumes and rely on the growth of retail
deposits from accrued interest.
Some large lenders even say they can live with the narrow margins between
saving and lending rates. Mr John Bayliss, Abbey National retail oper-ations
director, said: 'We have no intention of cutting our savings rates as things
stand. We do not need to do so.'
Things look rather different for small societies. They have to woo savers
hard to stay in business. They are less able to tap commercial money markets
and are reliant on volatile deposits from savers with a high net worth who
shift money quickly when a better rate is available elsewhere.
In recognition of this, Halifax yesterday tapered the reductions in its
investment rates to favour customers with deposits of more than Pounds
50,000.
The building society world has until now been used to a fairly tidy and
uniform interest rate structure. What has emerged in the last week looks
anything but uniform. There are clear signs of polarisation between the
large societies and smaller ones.
As to whether the new rates are sustainable, Mr Kirkham said: 'It all
depends on how we fare in the savings market in the next few months. If
societies do not get the inflow of savings that they need, then there will
have to be a change eventually.'
THE INLAND REVENUE is to launch a probe of individuals claiming to be
non-taxpayers and receiving interest gross from banks and building
societies, after discovering that up to a million of them are liable for
tax, Andrew Jack writes.
Investigators have found that up to 14 per cent of the 7m individuals who
have registered to receive interest gross earn income in excess of their
tax-free allowances.
The audit of claimants by tax inspectors has been triggered by market
research backed up by internal investigations and approaches to individuals
claiming to be non-taxpayers and receiving gross interest at levels close to
their allowances.
The revenue yesterday played down the possibility of widespread deliberate
fraud. It said: 'We think that mostly this is a case of people
misunderstanding the rules.'
Individuals whom investigators conclude have deliberately falsely registered
could be liable for fines of up to Pounds 3,000 and penalties up to the
value of the tax they should have paid.
</TEXT>
