FT  14 AUG 92 / Miners in radical S African accord
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A radical agreement signed by labour and management at the Harmony gold mine
in the Orange Free State opens the way to more co-operative labour relations
in the South African gold-mining industry, writes Philip Gawith from
Johannesburg.
The agreement, between the National Union of Mineworkers (NUM) and Harmony,
the biggest gold mine in South Africa and a member of the Rand Mines group,
includes a pay increase of less than 2.5 per cent, profit-sharing, reduction
of the effect of absenteeism on production, and the introduction of a
'collective bargaining fund'. It also provides for negotiations with the NUM
on new work practices and new technology to improve efficiency, negotiations
on skill training and an improved production bonus.
