<HEADLINE>
FT  14 AUG 92 / Halifax savings rate cut eases home loan fears
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD and SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PROSPECT of a rise in mortgage interest rates receded yesterday when
Halifax Building Society, the largest UK mortgage lender, announced that it
was cutting interest rates on its savings accounts by an average of 0.35
percentage points.
The move follows similar savings rate cuts by three other of the top 10
building societies in the past week and will affect about 14m savers.
Mr Mike Whitehouse, Halifax operations director, said: 'The Halifax has
sought to keep mortgage rates down throughout the year but, in common with
other societies, continuing pressures on operating margins means that
adjustments to investors' interest rates are required to ensure continued
financial strength for all our customers. The alternative of increasing
mortgage rates is not realistic.'
Most of the remaining large societies are expected to follow Halifax by
lowering their savings rates in the next few days. However, Abbey National,
the retail bank and second largest UK mortgage lender, said it would leave
its interest rates unchanged for the immediate future.
Halifax's decision was taken in spite of the news of an expected record
outflow of money from building society savings accounts in July, even larger
than a net outflow of Pounds 314m in June caused by stiff competition from
National Savings.
The Halifax cuts have been designed to penalise the largest balances the
least. The rates paid on Pounds 50,000 or more in the 90-day Xtra account
has been cut from 9.9 per cent gross to 9.8 per cent, compared with a
reduction from 8.85 per cent gross to 8.5 per cent on amounts from Pounds
10,000 to just under Pounds 25,000.
Although the government has twice lowered interest rates on National Savings
accounts in the past three weeks, it is by no means clear that the building
societies will be able to hold their own for long in the highly-competitive
UK savings market.
Feeling the squeeze, Page 5
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
