</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Gap, one of the most respected specialty retailers in US, yesterday
reported a 10.2 per cent improvement in second-quarter profits, to Dollars
37.7m after tax.
The rise is scored on sales up from Dollars 523.1m to Dollars 614.1m, with
the San Francisco-based company's same-store sales improved by about 5 per
cent. This is a slower rate of growth than in the second quarter of 1991,
when same-store sales increased by 11 per cent.
However, given the 'difficult economic climate', The Gap's chairman, Mr
Donald Fisher expressed satisfaction at the figures.
The second-quarter earnings total takes profits after tax for the first six
months of 1992, to August 1, to Dollars 83m, compared with Dollars 75.1m a
year earlier. Sales were Dollars 1.2bn, against Dollars 1.01bn last time.
