<HEADLINE>
FT  14 AUG 92 / International Company News: Hang Seng Bank earnings rise 22%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON HOLBERTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HANG Seng Bank, the listed subsidiary of Hongkong and Shanghai Bank,
yesterday reported a 22 per cent rise in net profits to HKDollars 2.3bn
(USDollars 298m) in the six months to June 30, from HKDollars 1.9bn a year
earlier, and forecast a 67 per cent increase in dividends for the year.
The bank said it had reviewed its dividend policy in light of its decision
to report earnings on a fully-disclosed basis. Hongkong Bank, which owns
61.5 per cent of Hang Sang, moved to full disclosure when it bid for Midland
Bank earlier this year.
Mr Alexander Au, managing director and deputy chief executive, said in
future the bank intended to pay around half of its net profits in dividends
 -a third of which would be paid out at the interim stage. Previously it had
paid out a half of its reported earnings.
He said, however, the percentage increases in the pay-out this year were
exceptional and one-off. The increases reflected the move to full disclosure
and their scale would not be repeated in the coming years, he said.
Hang Sang said it would pay an interim dividend of 65 cents a share,
compared with 38 cents. It expected to pay not less than HKDollars 1.67 for
the year - an increase in total 1992 dividends of 67 per cent over the 1991
payout.
The bank said the Hong Kong economy had maintained its momentum in the first
half, with the trade sector performing well and domestic demand buoyant.
'Against this background, the group's deposit and loan growth both recorded
satisfactory progress during the first half.'
Mr Au said the bank registered some slight growth in mortgage lending but
there was evidence of a slowdown towards the end of the half year.
He said the 'star' performer for the bank was trade finance. There had also
been very brisk growth in exports, especially re-exports.
</TEXT>
