<DOCNO>FT923-7956</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CHRANACBFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920814
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  14 AUG 92 / UK Company News: Cost reductions behind Glynwed's
improvement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GLYNWED International reduced its workforce by 450 during the first half of
this year as management continued to assault costs.
Cost reductions and a fall in interest charges were the main factors behind
the 48 per cent rise in pre-tax profits, from Pounds 10.4m to Pounds 15.4m.
The fall in the number of employees worldwide meant that in the last 18
months the group had shed more than 1,800 jobs, taking the payroll down to
some 11,500 from a peak of 13,600 in 1989-90.
There had been little or no improvement in Glynwed's markets since the 1991
first half, reported Mr Gareth Davies, chairman. Even in the highly
profitable plastics division there had been a pause in the demand from key
customers, like British Gas and the water companies. Activity in the
engineering steels market remained low, although slightly higher than last
year.
Output from metals services businesses had been higher this year than in the
closing months of last, but remained lower than it was in the first half of
1991.
COMMENT
Glynwed may be trying more to penetrate overseas markets, but the fact
remains that about 70 per cent of its turnover is in the UK. The hopes it
had of a gradually strengthening domestic economy have been thwarted, like
everybody else's. Charting the course of profits is a question of setting
poor markets against financial gains from past and, no doubt, future cost
cutting. An outcome of Pounds 40m pre-tax for the year, translating into
earnings of 13p a share, does not look unreasonable. That gives the shares,
at 196p, a prospective multiple of 15; worth holding for an upturn in demand
next year or 1994.
</TEXT>
