<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Audit Commission, the local authority watchdog, will give as much
attention to the efficacy of local citizen's charters as to traditional
efficiency studies, its new controller said yesterday.
Mr Andrew Foster, the deputy chief executive of the National Health Service
appointed yesterday to succeed Mr Howard Davies, now director-general of the
CBI, said he would give priority to 'putting the user of public services at
the centre (of the commission's work) rather than having structure and
resources always at the centre'.
That will be welcomed by councils, often critical of the commission for
analysing efficiency in isolation from quality. Mr Foster said that up to 20
councils were inadequately prepared for the transfer of community care from
the NHS to local government next year.
