<HEADLINE>
FT  14 AUG 92 / World Trade News: Japanese vehicle industry alarmed by Nafta
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GORDON CRAMB
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE JAPANESE vehicle industry reacted with alarm yesterday to tougher
requirements for local content under the North American free trade agreement
(Nafta), which it said would particularly affect its car output in Canada,
Gordon Cramb reports from Tokyo.
Government and business leaders generally gave a cool response to the
tripartite pact, saying it seemed to increase barriers to goods from
outside.
Japan is asking Gatt's secretariat to set up a working party on the pact.
This would be charged with examining whether Wednesday's US-Canada-Mexico
agreement met Gatt requirements for member countries. The accord 'could be
inconsistent with Gatt principles,' said Mr Yasuo Tanabe, director of North
America trade policy planning at the Ministry of International Trade and
Industry.
His comments were echoed by the Japan Automobile Manufacturers' Association
(Jama), which described the agreement's provisions as counter to a freer
global trade system. Japan will also air its qualms with the three
countries. Officials made clear they were reserving judgment until then,
when they would also have seen the full text.
Mr Tanabe said Japan welcomed free trade pacts with 'a positive effect to
outside countries' flow of trade and investment and to global trade as a
whole'. The agreement should not deflect attempts to reach an overdue
conclusion to the Uruguay Round of world trade talks which should remain the
top policy issue for Gatt member nations.
Mr Hajime Ohta, director of international economic affairs at the Keidanren,
Japan's private-sector federation of economic groups, said that as in the
case of the US-Canada free trade pact, much would depend on how Nafta would
be interpreted and implemented. Operation of the accord would have to be
transparent to outsiders, but local content rules 'might be a violation of
the Gatt code'.
</TEXT>
