<HEADLINE>
FT  14 AUG 92 / International Company News: Thomson hit by drop in newspaper
advertising
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FIERCE competition in the UK travel market and continued weakness in North
American newspaper advertising helped lower Thomson Corp's second-quarter
earnings by 11 per cent.
The Canadian-controlled group, the UK's largest tour operator, reiterated it
was 'not prepared to concede market share' to its competitors in the travel
market. Despite heavy discounting of brochure prices, Thomson said it had
not cut back its summer holiday capacity. Although Thomson Travel's sales
climbed by 11 per cent in the second quarter, operating profits dipped to
USDollars 30m from Dollars 32m a year earlier.
The group as a whole reported a drop in second-quarter earnings to Dollars
70m, or 12 cents a share, from Dollars 79m, or 13 cents a year earlier.
Sales rose to Dollars 1.53bn from Dollars 1.4bn.
The fall was most pronounced at Thomson's North American newspapers, where
operating profits fell to Dollars 54m from Dollars 64m on virtually
unchanged sales. The company said prospects have receded of 'an imminent
economic recovery of sufficient strength to generate significantly higher
revenue growth'.
The UK regional newspaper business also remains weak, with the recession
more than offsetting gains in circulation and expanded advertising market
share.
Thomson Tour Operations' 1991/92 winter sales were 24 per cent higher than
the previous year, and sales of summer 1992 holidays were 'marginally
ahead'. But said over-capacity has resulted in prolonged price discounting.
By contrast, Lunn Poly, Thomson's travel shop subsidiary, posted a
substantial first-half profits increase.
</TEXT>
