<HEADLINE>
FT  14 AUG 92 / International Company News: Kerkorian ends bid for seat on
Chrysler board
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MYSTERY surrounds yesterday's decision by Mr Kirk Kerkorian, the billionaire
investor, to withdraw his request for representation on Chrysler's board.
The reversal comes less than a week after Mr Kerkorian indicated that he was
no longer willing to remain a passive investor in Chrysler.
Neither Chrysler nor Mr Kerkorian are revealing enough details to account
for Mr Kerkorian's change of heart after his meeting this week with Chrysler
executives, including chairman and chief executive Mr Lee Iacocca, his
designated successor Mr Robert Eaton, and Mr Malcolm Stamper, chairman of
the nominating committee of Chrysler's board.
Mr Kerkorian, who holds a 9.8 per cent stake in the car maker, had initially
cited concern about Mr Iacocca's future role at Chrysler as his reason for
pressing for stronger board representation. Mr Iacocca said in March that he
would step down at the end of this year.
Mr Kerkorian, a friend of Mr Iacocca's, said the recent discussions had
convinced him that the interests of Chrysler's shareholders are well
represented by its current board. He added that he was comfortable with Mr
Iacocca's plans to continue as a director of Chrysler and chairman of the
company's powerful executive committee after the end of the year.
Mr Iacocca, for his part, reiterated his confidence in Mr Eaton. 'I expect
to remain active in Chrysler's future and plan to continue to serve the best
interests of its shareholders,' he added.
Mr Iacocca's reluctance to abdicate at Chrysler has been no secret. He has
reportedly been unhappy with the company's board since it blocked his
attempts to extend his tenure as chairman and chief executive beyond the end
of this year. Yesterday's announcement leaves the question of whether this
was a storm in a tea cup or whether more was decided during the discussions
than either party is willing to reveal.
</TEXT>
