FT  14 AUG 92 / International Company News: Loral group wins battle for LTV
unit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE BIDDING war for the missiles and aircraft unit of LTV Corporation, the
bankrupt steel company, yesterday ended in victory for the Dollars 475m bid
from a group composed of Loral Corporation, Carlyle Group - an investment
banking firm - and Northrop, the defence contractor.
After a lengthy hearing in the Manhattan bankruptcy courts yesterday
afternoon, Judge Burton Lifland - overseeing the LTV bankruptcy - said that
he was willing to accept the Loral group's offer.
His endorsement came after a long recess in which final details of the offer
were hammered out. It also followed submissions from representatives of
various LTV creditors - including the Pension Benefit Guaranty Corporation,
the federal agency which underpins pension benefits and LTV's largest
creditor - that the Loral group's bid was the highest and best offer on the
table.
Creditors had been confronted by a rival offer from Martin Marietta, another
US defence contractor. This offer, however, remained at Dollars 440m
yesterday - although terms were adjusted to offer Dollars 425m in cash and
the remaining Dollars 15m in preferred stock.
Judge Lifland declined to allow a Dollars 10m payment to Martin Marietta if
its offer was topped by a better bid, but he did acknowledge that the
unsuccessful suitor had played an important role in the sale process. He
said he would permit a smaller Dollars 5m payment.
The auction of the missile and aircraft businesses represents the final
throes of the LTV bankruptcy, which has dragged on for over five years.
</TEXT>
