FT  13 AUG 92 / Elf and Amerada swap gas assets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIET SYCHRAVA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ELF Exploration UK, a sub-sidiary of the French state-owned oil company Elf
Aquitaine, has swapped North Sea assets with Amerada Hess, the US oil
company.
Elf, the fourth largest North Sea operator, said the deal would help it to
strengthen its position in the North Sea, and demonstrated its long-term
commitment to the area.
The deal gives Elf a 12.5 per cent interest in the Franklin discovery,
thought to be a potentially large gas field. Franklin, in Block 29/5b, is
very close to Elf's Elgin gas field, which is under appraisal, and the
company plans to develop the two together.
Elf said the deal would allow it to swap present for future production and
to consolidate its interests in the North Sea. If the appraisal is positive,
Elf will seek government approval to develop the fields in 1994, hoping for
first gas by 1998.
Amerada Hess will get Elf's 16.45 per cent interest in the Anglia gas field,
raising its total interest to 29.29 per cent. Anglia is producing 50m cu ft
of gas a day. Amerada Hess said the deal strengthened its position in the
southern gas basin of the North Sea.
