<HEADLINE>
FT  13 AUG 92 / Commercial Union cuts losses to Pounds 18m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMMERCIAL Union, one of the largest UK composite insurers, yesterday
announced an improved performance in the first six months of 1992 with
pre-tax losses falling to Pounds 18.1m compared with Pounds 26.3m at the
halfway stage last year.
CU posted a Pounds 2.3m profit in the second quarter, in spite of a Pounds
15m loss due to the IRA bombing its London headquarters in April.
First-half figures also indicated that CU, the most highly rated of the UK
composites, is continuing to increase premium income at a faster rate than
its rivals.
Overall underwriting losses fell to Pounds 205.2m from Pounds 228.3m, with
UK underwriting losses Pounds 95.4m against a loss of Pounds 104.3m.
Investment income (net of loan interest) declined to Pounds 129.4m from
Pounds 145.1m.
Life profits fell to Pounds 50.7m from Pounds 53.7m while associated
undertakings' earnings amounted to Pounds 7m, up from Pounds 3.2m. Post-tax
operating losses of Pounds 23.7m (up from Pounds 21.5m) were offset by
realised investment gains of Pounds 182.4m (against Pounds 36.4m). The
interim dividend was unchanged at 9.25p per share. There was a loss per
share of 5.4p, against 5p last time.
Mr Peter Ward, managing director UK, denied CU was 'pursuing an aggressive
policy' but accepted CU was 'writing new business when some of our
competitors are shedding business'.
Premium income from UK motor insurance rose 52.9 per cent to Pounds 102m,
reflecting rate increases and an 12 per cent increase in policyholders.
Overall UK premium income rose 19.2 per cent to Pounds 709.9m. Life premiums
grew 42 per cent to Pounds 272.2m, reflecting strong sales of a new single
premium bond. Mr Ward said CU was prioritising sales of motor policies to
drivers aged over 30 and preferred to limit cover to named drivers.
Mr Tom Bennett, analyst with Banque Paribas Capital Markets, said: 'The UK
account is going ahead at a hell of a rate.'
CU has benefited from its relatively low exposure to domestic mortgage
indemnity policies, which compensate lenders when they make losses on the
sale of repossessed homes.
The group has also been helped by its relatively low investment exposure in
the UK equity market. At Pounds 1.2bn, shareholders funds were only
marginally down on the year-end figure of Pounds 1.21bn although assets were
boosted by a Pounds 100m preference share issue in May. CU's solvency (net
assets as a percentage of non-life premiums) was 42.5 per cent, compared
with 44 per cent on December 31.
Lex, Page 14; Market, Page 32
