FT  13 AUG 92 / Maxwell law firm has bills queried
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A LAW firm working on the insolvency of Maxwell Communication Corporation
had its fees questioned yesterday in a US bankruptcy court, Andrew Jack
writes.
The judge also extended the deadline for the completion of a reorganisation
plan for MCC. Judge Tina Brosman granted administrators a 60-day extension
to October 13 to file the plan for the company - and said she was pleased
with the progress made so far.
Sitting in the South District of New York Court, the judge refused to
approve a Dollars 677,000 bill from Milbank Tweed Hadley and McCloy for work
in the three months to June 30.
She also queried payments to Price Waterhouse, the accountancy firm, and JP
Morgan, the merchant bank, but authorised their settlement.
Milbank Tweed said its bill covered 85 per cent of lawyers' hours over the
period, tax advice and clerical costs.
The judge queried fees of between Dollars 35 and Dollars 50 an hour for
paralegals faxing documents, photocopying papers and stuffing envelopes. The
firm defended the fees as comparable with those demanded by temporary
workers.
MCC is protected from creditors under Chapter 11 in the US, and through
administration under UK insolvency law.
