<HEADLINE>
FT  13 AUG 92 / TUC calls for Pounds 600m for training and jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT was urged by trade unions yesterday to spend Pounds 600m on
measures to tackle unemployment, ahead of official figures today that are
expected to show that the number of jobless has risen for the 28th
consecutive month.
The Trades Union Congress drew attention to a recent analysis by the
Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD), showing that
Britain lagged behind most European Community nations in developing labour
market measures to tackle joblessness.
The TUC wants the government to restore the budgets of Training and
Enterprise Councils, which administer training in England and Wales, and
also to develop temporary employment programmes.
Separately, Mr Bill Jordan, president of the AEEU engineering and electrical
union, called on the TUC and the Confederation of British Industry to seek a
meeting with the prime minister to urge measures to halt economic decline.
The TUC said Britain was ranked ninth out of 12 EC countries in the OECD
analysis in terms of the percentage of national income spent on training,
temporary work programmes and job subsidies. Spending an estimated 0.56 per
cent of national income last year, Britain ranked only just above Portugal
and Greece. Five EC countries spent nearly twice as much as Britain.
Mr Norman Willis, TUC general secretary, said Britain's job record was a
'cause for national shame'. He added: 'At a time when the government should
be taking action to cut the dole queues, all it appears to be doing is
stoking up rumours about reducing the benefit of the growing number of
long-term unemployed.'
Today's figures are expected to show that the unemployment figure for June
of 2.72m rose by a further 25,000 in July.
Mr John Major has held the first meeting of a UK prime minister with Civil
Service union leaders since 1984, it emerged yesterday.
The discussion at 10 Downing Street, which came after the government
restricted pay rises for high-salaried public servants, is seen by unions as
evidence that Mr Major is taking a less hostile approach to them than his
predecessor.
The last meeting between a prime minister and Civil Service unions came when
the then Mrs Margaret Thatcher defended the union ban at the Government
Communications Headquarters, Cheltenham.
According to the monthly journal of the FDA civil servants association, Mr
Major told general secretaries of the FDA, IPMS and NUCPS unions on July 29
that he regretted the decision to cut rises of up to 24 per cent, as
recommended by the top salaries review body, to 4 per cent. However, he said
many individuals had had pay rises of below 4 per cent and others had
received pay cuts.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
