<HEADLINE>
FT  13 AUG 92 / Bingham made Master of Rolls
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LORD JUSTICE Bingham, the Appeal Court judge who has just completed an
11-month inquiry into the collapsed Bank of Credit and Commerce
International, was yesterday appointed Master of the Rolls in succession to
Lord Donaldson.
Lord Donaldson retires at the end of next month after 10 years as the most
senior civil court judge in England and Wales.
The BCCI report is expected to be published before Sir Thomas takes up his
new office on September 30.
Sir Thomas, 58, is widely regarded by the legal profession as having one of
the best intellects on the bench and as a radical who is willing to speak
his mind.
In 1989 he was the first judge to speak out strongly in favour of Lord
Mackay's proposed reforms of the legal profession. To the surprise of many
barristers and judges, Sir Thomas said the greatest threat to barristers was
not the reforms but the profession's negative reaction to them.
The rules preventing solicitors from appearing as advocates in the higher
courts were illogical, indefensible and could not be justified, he said.
In marked contrast to the attitude of Lord Donaldson, who warned the Lord
Chancellor to 'get your tanks off my lawn', Sir Thomas dismissed the
suggestions of his fellow judges that Lord Mackay's reforms threatened
judicial independence and were not wanted by the public.
He said: 'We delude ourselves if we suppose there is not a large body of
responsible, middle-of-the-road opinion that regards the legal profession as
riddled with anachronistic conventions and privileges.'
Sir Thomas, the only son of two doctors, was educated at Sedbergh and
Balliol College, Oxford, where he took a first in modern history. He was
called to the Bar by Gray's Inn in 1959 after coming top in the Bar exams
and rapidly earned recognition as one of the brightest commercial lawyers of
his generation and a brilliant advocate.
He took silk at the age of 38 in 1972 and was appointed to the High Court
bench in 1980. In 1986 he was promoted to the Court of Appeal.
He is no stranger to controversy. In 1977 he was appointed by Dr David Owen,
then foreign secretary, to head the inquiry into Rhodesia sanctions-busting
by the big UK oil companies. His report concluded that they had knowingly
violated United Nations sanctions, and that government officials were aware
of that.
In 1982 he conducted an inquiry for the Lord Chancellor into the issues
raised by the contempt-of-court action brought against the government by Ms
Harriet Harman, now Labour MP for Peckham in south London, over
non-disclosure of documents.
During the 1991 Gulf war he was one of the 'three wise men' who reviewed
cases of Arabs facing deportation as security risks.
Lord Justice Bingham is known to share the concerns of the present Master of
the Rolls about the delays and costs of the civil justice system.
Mr Mark Sheldon, president of the Law Society, the solicitors' governing
body, welcomed the appointment, and praised Sir Thomas as 'a lawyer of great
intellect with a reputation for innovation and an open-minded approach to
reform'.
The society hopes that as one of the four designated judges who must decide
on wider rights of audience for solicitors, Sir Thomas will prove a
formidable ally.
The Bar Council, the barristers' ruling body, also welcomed the appointment.
Mr John Rowe QC, vice-chairman, said Sir Thomas was 'forward-looking' and
'likely to bring innovation to civil justice'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
