<HEADLINE>
FT  13 AUG 92 / Cadbury has basic 'majority backing'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE MAJORITY of res-pondents to the Cadbury committee report on corporate
governance have been 'generally supportive' of the initiative but have
detailed reservations about some of its suggestions.
Staff serving the committee said yesterday that 64 per cent of those who
expressed a view about its recommendations were in that category. Among them
were the Confederation of British Industry which, while supporting the
report in principle, objected to the enforcement mechanisms suggested by the
committee.
An analysis of the 70 responses to the report, prepared by committee staff,
showed that only 16 per cent of respondents opposed its recommendations,
against 20 per cent who were were 'very supportive'.
The committee, known informally by the name of its chairman, Sir Adrian
Cadbury, issued a draft report in May recommending a code of best practice
to be followed by corporate boards of directors.
The code, which is voluntary, is intended to improve the performance and
financial reporting of companies.
Aspects of the report have been criticised by those who will be most
affected by them. Some leading industrialists say that the report has gone
too far, while some institutional shareholders have objected that it does
not go far enough.
Staff serving the Cadbury committee said that a significant minority of
respondents - 25 out of 70 - expressed no general view about the proposals
as a whole, but simply offered comments about aspects of the report.
</TEXT>
