<HEADLINE>
FT  13 AUG 92 / Watchdog warns on loan loss provision
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUILDING SOCIETIES have been asked by the Building Societies Commission, the
industry watchdog, to consider ways of tightening up their provisions
against loan losses.
The move is likely to squeeze building society profits further by forcing
societies to put more money aside at a time when they are already suffering
from the decline in house sales.
Mr Harry Walsh, deputy chairman of the Building Societies Commission, has
written to the Building Societies Association asking for its views on new
guidelines on provisions after consulting its members.
This is the second year in succession in which the commission has tried to
introduce guidelines for loan loss provisions as a result of the deepening
troubles of the mortgage market. Before 1990, loan losses were usually so
small that the definition of building society provisions was not an issue.
Last year societies were forced to put aside a total of Pounds 1.23bn
against bad loans, and the figure for the coming year is expected to be
higher. About half a dozen societies, including Town &amp; Country and
Leamington Spa, have been driven into pre-tax losses and been forced to give
up their independence after having to make heavy provisions against bad
loans.
Last year the commission's guidelines encouraged societies to make specific
provisions for losses on residential mortgages for all cases where payments
are more than three months in arrears and it is virtually certain that the
lender will make a loss.
Most societies also make general provisions against likely losses on their
mortgage book as a whole. They also 'suspend' interest on loans with a low
chance of recovery, thus reducing the value of the interest receivable on
their accounts. Methods for doing so vary greatly between so-cieties.
The commission says it wants a standard method of recognising the interest
due on non-performing loans and the formal adoption of a three-month cut-off
point for specific provision and of a standard definition of arrears. It
also wants societies to consider methods of security valuation.
Alliance &amp; Leicester, the fourth-largest building society, said it was
cutting rates for its 3.2m savers by an average 0.3 per cent from Saturday.
The move follows similar cuts by Nationwide and Bradford &amp; Bingley and
suggests that large societies are determined to stave off any increase in
mortgage interest rates for as long as possible.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
