FT  13 AUG 92 / Former company secretary charged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MR ANTHONY John Smithson, a former company secretary of Arrows
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
the Cheshire-based trade finance house owned by Mr Muhammad Naviede which
collapsed a year ago - was arrested yesterday at his Manchester home by City
of London police, Ian Hamilton Fazey writes.
He was charged at Bishopsgate police station with obtaining property by
deception and dishonestly obtaining services. Mr Smithson's arrest follows a
year-long investigation by the Serious Fraud Office into Arrows. Mr Naviede
was charged last August with obtaining Pounds 10m by deception from ABN Bank
of the Netherlands. The money was lent to Arrows for stock-financing
operations for its corporate customers, but is alleged to have found its way
into property investments that then suffered in the recession.
Total debts of more than 80 companies and single-purpose trusts connected
with Arrows have been put at about Pounds 220m by Mr Scott Martin and Mr
Nigel Hamilton of Ernst &amp; Young, the group's liquidator. There is a
shortfall of about Pounds 100m and Arrows' own debts are understood to total
Pounds 113m. Creditors include 35 banks or building societies.
Mr Smithson was remanded on bail until October 21 on condition he live at
home, surrender his passport and pilot's licence and enter an aircraft only
as a fare-paying passenger on an internal UK flight. Mr Naviede is already
on Pounds 400,000 bail and has had to surrender his passport and pilot's
licence.
</TEXT>
