<HEADLINE>
FT  13 AUG 92 / Washington may approve aircraft sale to Saudis
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY WALKER and ROGER MATTHEWS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CAIRO, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A US AGREEMENT on Dollars 10bn (Pounds 5.2bn) in loan guarantees for Israel
brought warnings yesterday that it could endanger the Middle East peace
process and an indication that the administration might be willing to
proceed with a Saudi Arabian request for a Dollars 5bn military aircraft
order.
In Washington, efforts began in Congress almost immediately to extract
concessions from President George Bush on other issues, in order to
facilitate speedy passage of the loan agreement. Senator Christopher Bond
urged the administration to proceed with the sale of additional F-15 fighter
aircraft to Saudi Arabia and warned that 40,000 jobs, the majority of them
in his home state of Missouri, could be at stake if Riyadh's request was not
approved.
A US official said later that the president was seriously considering the
sale, which had been requested last year. He denied that further
consideration of the sale was linked to the loans guarantee agreement with
Israel.
Mr Yitzhak Rabin, Israel's prime minister, was quick to fire a warning shot
across the bows of any scheme to sell additional F-15s to Saudi Arabia. 'No
official or responsible politician in Israel can but oppose the sale of arms
to an Arab country that continues to stress that it is in a state of war
with Israel,' he told a lunch at the press club in Washington.
He said that although people argued that Saudi Arabia was an ally of the US,
Israel remembered that positive views had been expressed about the
intentions of President Saddam Hussein only a few months before Iraq invaded
Kuwait.
Mr Rabin was also worried by reports that it would be the F-15E that might
be sold to Saudi Arabia, an aircraft more advanced that those supplied to
Israel.
Saudi Arabia has asked for up to 62 F-15 aircraft as part of its military
expansion programme following the defeat of Iraqi forces in Kuwait. Saudi
officials have warned privately that if the US was unable to meet the order
it might have to turn to Britain for additional Tornado aircraft.
Meanwhile, Palestinians have charged the administration with bias for
providing the loan guarantees needed by Israel in its attempts to absorb a
flood of Soviet immigrants.
Mrs Hanan Ashrawi, Palestinian spokeswoman, said that 'if the loan
guarantees are given while settlement activities are continuing, then this
invalidates the role of the US as a peace broker'.
Negative Arab reaction can be seen partly as posturing ahead of the
resumption of peace talks with Israel in Washington later this month. Arab
officials have indicated greater understanding in private of domestic
pressures on both Mr Rabin and Mr Bush.
Congressional leaders have told Mr Bush there is no prospect of the loan
guarantees being approved before September, and there are still doubts over
whether Mr Bush and Mr Rabin agreed that the cost of completing houses
already under construction in the occupied territories should be deducted
from the total amount the US will guar-antee.
Israel sought yesterday to reinforce its claims that it was doing all it
could to rein in settlements by announcing a freeze on house purchases in
Arab East Jerusalem. It also announced that apartments acquired by the
Housing Ministry under the previous pro-settlement Likud government would
not be renovated.
Israel's cabinet strongly condemned earlier this week a move by about 15
Jewish families into seven houses purchased in the Moslem quarter of the
walled city.
The Bush administration had refused to provide the loan guarantees - needed
by Israel to borrow at preferential rates internationally - to the outgoing
government of Mr Yitzhak Shamir because of its refusal to stop building
settlements in territories captured in the 1967 war.
Full details of the agreement reached by Mr Rabin and Mr Bush at the
president's Kennebunkport holiday retreat have not been divulged but the
Israeli leader intimated they had reached private understanding after some
difficult discussions.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
