<HEADLINE>
FT  13 AUG 92 / Manufacturers report falls in output and export orders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DOMESTIC and overseas demand for manufactured goods failed to live up to
post-election expectations in all but one region of the UK.
Manufacturers in almost every region also reported a fall in output over the
past four months and all reported continuing job losses in a survey which
showed that southern England and the West Midlands remain the areas worst
affected by the recession.
According to the latest survey of regional trends from the Confederation of
British Industry (CBI) and Business Strategies Limited (BSL), the decline in
orders since April was due to worse-than-expected export orders and a sharp
decline in demand for intermediate goods.
Northern Ireland was the only region to experience an increase in demand for
manufactured goods. It was also one of only three regions - the others being
the East Midlands and East Anglia - to report a slight rise in output,
against eight that expected an improvement when last surveyed in April.
The outlook for employment remained grim, with manufacturing job losses
reported in every region. The fastest falls were in the West Midlands, the
north-west, south-west and south-east, but the rate of job shedding eased in
Wales, East Anglia and the East Midlands.
Official figures out today are expected to show there was another big rise
in unemployment in July. Yesterday, the Alfred Marks Bureau, an employment
agency, said vacancies for full-time jobs fell by 8 per cent in July
compared with a year ago.
Mr Robin Cook, shadow trade and industry secretary, said the survey showed
that British business was losing hope. 'There is no point ranking each
region to see which is doing worst. The key point of this survey is that all
regions are in trouble,' he said.
The CBI and BSL pointed out that earlier expectations of rising orders of
intermediate goods proved misplaced. A recovery in such goods, which are
used as inputs by other industries, is a frequent development at the
beginning of an upturn. In fact, regions with a high concentration of
companies manufacturing intermediate goods, such as chemicals and metals,
suffered the most disappointing falls in output. These included the north
and Yorkshire and Humberside.
Scotland, the region with the smallest proportion of intermediate goods
manufacturers, fared better than other regions, while Wales, due to its good
export performance, was also less badly affected.
N Ireland bucks downward trend in demand, Page 5
</TEXT>
