<HEADLINE>
FT  13 AUG 92 / N American free trade deal opens up 'new era': US, Canada
and Mexico agree on pact after 14 months of negotiations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE, DAMIAN FRASER and BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, MEXICO CITY, TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NORTH AMERICAN leaders yesterday hailed the completion of negotiations to
bring together the US, Canada and Mexico as one of the world's two largest
free trade areas.
President George Bush said a 'new era' opened up with the historic
agreement, creating a powerful trading zone of 360m consumers and annual
economic output worth about Dollars 6,000bn.
Its formation has been spurred on by plans to widen free trade in western
Europe, with the eventual setting up of a 19-nation European Economic Area
of 380m consumers. It reflects North American worries about the deadlock in
the Uruguay Round of talks on world trade liberalisation and concern about
the possible emergence of an inward-looking 'Fortress Europe'.
The North American Free Trade Agreement (Nafta) was stitched together in 14
months of talks, ending with 10 days of intense parlaying in a Washington
hotel. The US pressed for completion in time for the Republican party
convention which will re-nominate Mr Bush for president next week.
Appearing in the White House rose garden with Mrs Carla Hills, the US trade
representative, Mr Bush said Nafta was 'part of my long-term economic growth
plan'. He said booming trade with Mexico had already created 600,000 US jobs
and more would be created.
Nafta will phase out tariffs and other trade barriers between the US, Canada
and Mexico over 15 years and is expected to lead to restructuring of whole
industries.
It is an unprecedented 'mixed marriage' linking two industrialised powers
with a third world nation. It joins the capital, technology and creativity
of the US and Canada with the cheap labour and resources of Mexico.
But Nafta still has to be approved by the legislatures of all three
countries and it faces some strong opposition, especially in Canada and
among US congressmen who fear loss of jobs to Mexico and lower environmental
standards.
Mr Bush said Nafta broke new ground for trade pacts by including 'stringent
provisions' on the environment. But he gave no promise of retraining or
assistance programmes for the thousands of US workers - mostly high-wage
factory workers - likely to lose their jobs as companies are drawn south to
the Mexico-US border area.
Under Nafta, Mexico for the first time will open its market to US cars,
light trucks and motor vehicle parts. After 15 years, the agreement will
guarantee total market access in agriculture.
It is the first trade agreement to eliminate quotas on textiles among its
parties. It is also the first to create free trade in services, opening
Mexico's telecoms and insurance markets.
In a vigorous defence of Nafta, President Carlos Salinas de Gortari of
Mexico said it would generate more jobs and better pay for Mexicans. But the
benefits would not come immediately, he warned. Nafta was not a 'magic
formula to resolve all our problems', he said.
Nafta reflects a radical change in Mexico's economic and foreign policy in
the past five years. Once deeply suspicious of both the US and free trade,
Mexico is now embracing both.
Mr Salinas said the treaty would make Mexico one of the centres of the world
economy.
Mr Michael Wilson, Canadian trade minister, called the Nafta deal a 'very
good agreement' for his country. But many Canadians blame the three-year-old
US-Canada free trade agreement for job losses and other economic ills and
fear a further shake-up from the wider pact with Mexico.
Page 3
Mexican needs create a job-making pact
Trade set to inch up US political agenda
World wary of Fortress America syndrome
Page 12
