FT  13 AUG 92 / International Company News: Capital injection of FM 1.7bn
for Finnish bank
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
KANSALLIS-Osake-Pankki (KOP), Finland's largest commercial bank, announced
yesterday that it would take a FM 1.7bn (Dollars 422m) financial injection
from the Finnish government to strengthen its capital base and improve its
capital requirement ratio.
The capital provision will bring an estimated immediate increase of about
FM20bn in the bank's lending capacity. The group's half-year results, due to
be released at the end of next month, are expected to show a continuing
loss.
The capital injection comes from a FM8bn provision made by the Finnish
government in June to strengthen the capital base of Finnish banks. This
follows the creation earlier in the year of a FM20bn government deposit
guarantee fund established in response to a serious deterioration in the
country's banking sector caused by mounting loan losses.
The financial injection to KOP takes the form of a preferred capital
certificate and carries a coupon of 0.50 per cent a year over one-year
Finnish government Treasury bills until the end of 1997.
Mr Pertti Voutilainen, chairman and chief executive, said that the bank had
been looking at ways of strengthening its capital base to ensure capital
adequacy requirements would 'under no circumstances' constrain its
operations. 'The capital investment offered by the state has turned out to
be the most attractive alternative,' he added.
As a result of the capital injection, KOP said its capital ratio will rise
by nearly 1.5 per cent under both Bank of International Settlement and local
regulations. At the end of April the ratio stood at 8.9 per cent.
Since he became head of KOP last February, Mr Voutilainen has been carrying
out a comprehensive programme of rationalisation of its organisation which
has included halving the size of its executive committee, a cut of 10 per
cent in the bank's payroll by the end of the year and a shift in the focus
of KOP's activities to basic banking services through a reallocation of its
capital from real estate.
</TEXT>
