<HEADLINE>
FT  13 AUG 92 / Government Bonds: Australian sell-off after hopes of rate
cut dashed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARA WEBB and PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DEALERS reported heavy selling of Australian government bonds yesterday
after Mr John Dawkins, the Australian treasurer, dashed hopes of a cut in
interest rates.
The bond market had expected to see an easing in rates fairly soon, possibly
timed to follow the Budget on August 18. However, Mr Dawkins said in a radio
interview: 'As far as we are concerned, there have been very considerable
falls in interest rates already. And the consequences of those reductions
are flowing through into the economy now.'
He added that given the prevailing domestic and international circumstances
he saw no need for 'any further easings in monetary policy'. The yield on
the 10 1/2 per cent September 1995 bond rose from 6.60 per cent to 6.88 per
cent and dealers reported heavy selling of bonds in Australia and overseas.
Traders warned that Mr Dawkins' comments were probably aimed at supporting
the Australian dollar, which has weakened from USDollars 0.74 last week to
below USDollars 0.72, its lowest level since February 1988.
GOOD news on inflation and a reasonably successful afternoon auction of
10-year securities failed to give US Treasury prices a lift yesterday.
In late trading the benchmark 30-year government bond was down  11/32 at 107
27/32 , yielding 7.338 per cent. The two-year note was also lower, down
3/32 at 100 5/32 to yield 4.149 per cent. Trading activity was extremely
quiet.
The day's main economic news was the release of the producer prices index
for July, which was up 0.1 per cent on the month.
Although the auction subsequently went off well - the notes were awarded at
an average yield of 6.49 per cent - the result was slightly below
expectations, and prices retreated further during the afternoon.
RUMOURS that Moody's, the international rating agency, is about to downgrade
Italy's credit rating, helped to push down Italian government bond prices
yesterday.
The May 2002 bond fell from 93.86 to a low of 93.50 before closing at 93.58,
and dealers reported determined selling by European investors.
Elsewhere in the European government bond markets, German government debt
drifted lower as the Bundesbank's decision to drain liquidity from the money
market yesterday sparked fears of a possible rise in German interest rates.
At its latest one-month securities repurchase allocation, the Bundesbank
drained DM2.4bn of liquidity from the money market, a larger-than-expected
withdrawal of funds. 'The market is sensing a hike in the Lombard rate,'
said one dealer.
The fall in the other European markets also helped to depress bund prices,
and the Liffe bund futures contract fell from 87.28 at the opening to end at
87.16.
STERLING's weakness in the foreign exchange markets helped to push UK
government bonds lower, with prices falling across the yield curve.
The 11 3/4 per cent gilt due 2003/07 fell from 115 to 114 19/32 to yield 9.5
per cent while the 10 1/2 per cent gilt due 1997 declined from 103 9/16 to
103 3/8 .
JAPANESE government bond prices ended firmer as the weak state of the Tokyo
stock market continued to kindle hopes of lower interest rates.
The Nikkei stock index ended down 48.77 points at 14,773.79 yesterday, still
below the psychologically important 15,000 level. The benchmark No 129 JGB
opened with a yield of 4.955 per cent and traded up to yield 4.915 per cent.
In the futures market, volumes in the December contract surpassed that in
the September contract, making it the new lead contract.
</TEXT>
