<DOCNO>FT923-8217</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CHNBSAFGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920812
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 92 / Price barrier
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Mann, sales manager at Titan Forge Ltd in east London, was not
surprised to hear that factory gate prices - the colloquial shorthand for
Britain's producer prices index - rose at the slowest rate since 1968 in the
year to July, Emma Tucker writes.
The company, supplier of iron railings, balustrades and gates, has not been
able to raise the prices of its factory gates for more than three years.
'Prices have been cut to the bone. Sometimes the amount we charge for work
just covers the wages,' said Mr Mann.
Sentiment is the same at Cornwell &amp; O'Neil, an industrial and domestic gate
manufacturer in Greenwich, south-east London. Mr Roy Wilkinson, a partner,
said prices at his company had not moved for at least two years. 'Raising
prices? We're too frightened,' he said. 'The government needs to cut
interest rates and let inflation go - why not?'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
