<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 92 / Rising costs undermine profitability of unit trusts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HALF of all unit trust companies earned marginal profits or made losses in
1991, mainly reflecting spiralling costs of sales and distribution,
according to a survey.
Mr Derek Ross, partner at Touche Ross Management Consultants, said the
firm's latest industry survey showed that there was still significant
over-capacity in the sector and that consolidation was likely. 'The main
point is rationalisation,' he said. 'There are too many unit trusts.'
Recent figures from the Unit Trust Association, the industry trade
association, show that last year the number of unit holder accounts, at
4.46m, was the lowest since 1987. The number of trusts, at 1,400, was also
marginally below the peak. There were 157 separate unit trust companies,
compared with 139 in 1987, the peak year for net new investment, according
to the UTA.
The study shows that most unit trust companies made losses on the sales side
of their businesses, but many were able to recoup through operating charges
on ongoing business. Larger companies showed little benefit from economies
of scale, because cost savings on sales were eaten up by the higher
commissions and fee discounting they were forced to offer to remain
competitive.
The study concludes: 'Despite the scale cost advantages that large companies
enjoy, they do not appear to have converted them into a significant lead in
staff efficiency when compared with their smaller rivals.'
Mr Ross said Touche Ross had reviewed the three main sales channels -
independent financial advisers, direct sales and group sales forces - and
found that none was profitable.
Of the three channels, independent financial advisers accounted for nearly
60 per cent of all sales. Group sales forces, which accounted for 19.3 per
cent of all sales, incurred the highest commission costs and paid the
highest rebates of fees to unit holders.
Touche Ross Unit Trust Managers Survey 1991. Touche Ross, Peterborough
Court, 133 Fleet Street, London EC4A 2TR. Pounds 705.
</TEXT>
