FT  12 AUG 92 / Tec issues ultimatum on training
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Central England Training and Enterprise Council (Centec) has given the
hundreds of companies who contract with it a tough training ultimatum.
It has given its suppliers until November 1993 to register as committed to
Investors in People (IIP) or forfeit grants for training and enterprise
initiatives. Centec's budget this year was about Pounds 10m.
Centec, based in the West Midlands, is the first Tec to adopt such a policy
of contract compliance. Others among the 82 Tecs in England and Wales may
follow.
Mr Edward Roberts, Centec chairman, also chairs G10, the group of 10 Tec
chairmen that liaises with the government on broad issues. IIP was
introduced last year as a means of evaluating the process of training.
Companies have to convince Tec assessors that they undertake a range of
quality assurance actions - for example, that they regularly review the
training and development of all their employees.
Government and Tecs, which are responsible for accrediting companies with a
kitemark for training quality, hope that IIP will be a driving force for the
improvement of training.
The scheme has taken off slowly, with only 68 companies accredited, although
more than 1,000 throughout the UK have registered as committed to it. The
Department of Employment yesterday published a report saying its Restart
programme, which provides unemployed people with advisory interviews every
six months, has proved highly successful.
The Policy Studies Institute report says Restart brought a number of
benefits, including getting more people into jobs.
The Restart Effect. BEBC Distribution, PO Box 1496, Poole, Dorset BH12 3YD.
Pounds 14.95.
